  "prompt": "What are traditional British dishes?",
  "response": "Traditional British cuisine is rich and diverse, reflecting the country's history and regional variations. Some classic British dishes include:\n\n1. **Fish and Chips:** Deep-fried battered fish (typically cod or haddock) served with chunky, deep-fried potatoes. Often accompanied by mushy peas and tartar sauce.\n\n2. **Sunday Roast:** A traditional meal served on Sundays, usually consisting of roasted meat (beef, lamb, or chicken), roasted potatoes, Yorkshire pudding, stuffing, and a variety of vegetables, all topped with gravy.\n\n3. **Full English Breakfast:** A hearty breakfast including bacon, sausages, fried eggs, baked beans, grilled tomatoes, mushrooms, black pudding, and toast. Sometimes accompanied by hash browns and fried bread.\n\n4. **Shepherd's Pie:** A dish made with minced lamb (or beef for Cottage Pie) cooked with onions and vegetables, topped with mashed potatoes and baked until golden brown.\n\n5. **Bangers and Mash:** Sausages served with mashed potatoes, often accompanied by onion gravy and peas.\n\n6. **Steak and Kidney Pie:** A savory pie filled with diced steak and kidneys, cooked in a rich gravy and encased in pastry.\n\n7. **Yorkshire Pudding:** A savory baked pudding made from batter (flour, eggs, and milk), often served as part of a Sunday roast.\n\n8. **Cornish Pasty:** A pastry filled with meat (usually beef), potatoes, onions, and sometimes swedes, traditionally from Cornwall.\n\n9. **Bubble and Squeak:** A dish made from leftover vegetables (typically cabbage and potatoes) from a Sunday roast, fried together until crispy.\n\n10. **Ploughman's Lunch:** A simple cold meal, typically comprising cheese, pickles, bread, and salad.\n\n11. **Toad in the Hole:** Sausages baked in a Yorkshire pudding batter, usually served with onion gravy and vegetables.\n\n12. **Welsh Rarebit:** A savory dish made with melted cheese on toast, often mixed with ale, mustard, and spices.\n\n13. **Scotch Eggs:** Hard-boiled eggs wrapped in sausage meat, breaded and deep-fried.\n\n14. **Chicken Tikka Masala:** An example of British Indian cuisine, consisting of grilled marinated chicken pieces in a creamy spiced sauce. \n\nThese dishes are just a snapshot of the rich, comforting, and often hearty cuisine that represents traditional British food.",
